Etymology. Succuba (paramour, Latin)—a folkloric demon that appears in dreams and takes a form of a woman in order to seduce men. The name refers to the serrated submarginal line unusual for the genus members, and wavy outer margin of a hindwing—in the Medieval culture succubae were often pictured and sculptured as a beautiful young girl possessing demonic features such as serrated wings, bird claws or serpentine tails (
Davidson 2012
).

